segments.text: You were born in Rockdale?
I was here at the mine, the broken mine.
You were born at the old mine?
Yeah, I was born there.
I was raised and born there.
I lived in Bonne Conde all my life.
How old were you when you went into the mines?
What?
How old were you when you went into the mines?
I was about 18 when I worked in there.
I worked in there about six months here.
I wasn't old enough, you know.
I worked about six months.
I went down there with Daddy, you know.
Your dad?
I went down to Lexington.
Yeah, Daddy, yeah.
Where did your dad come from?
He came from Germany.
What part of Germany?
I don't remember.
Did your mother come from Germany also?
Yeah, she came too with his kids, yeah.
Okay.
So you only worked in the mines about six months?
Yeah, I did.
Yeah, Daddy, he worked long, you know.
Yeah, he did.
Well, did you actually go in, down inside the mine?
Yeah, I went down in there.
Yeah, I went down in there.
What kind of tools did you use?
Pick and shovel.
Pick and shovel?
Yeah, pick and shovel.
Carbide lamps, you know.
Yeah.
Hang up here.
Right, yeah.
How many hours a day would you work on average?
Ah, they wouldn't work more than me.
Eight.
Eight to five.
That's about ten hours.
Nine hours.
Nine hours, yeah.
Would you eat down inside the mine?
Yeah, we'd eat down there.
The Mexicans, they'd take their lunch along down there.
They wouldn't come out until evening, you know, about four or five.
I see.
You lived at the mine site?
Yeah, I lived out there.
I was born out there.
Could you describe the house in which you lived?
The what?
The house where you lived out there at the mines?
What did it look like?
Oh, it was an old house, kind of like this here, but you know.
Was it painted or?
No, it wasn't painted.
No, it wasn't painted.
Well, how many rooms were in the house?
Lewis, you know how many rooms was in our house?
How many rooms in our house?
How many rooms in our house?
Yeah.
It's a big family.
It was 12 kids in the family.
What?
Seven with the bag.
Oh, she's talking about this house?
What?
Seven with the bag.
Seven with the bag, at least she said.
Out there at the mine.
At the mine, yeah.
And then they had two porches on it, you know, honestly.
Old-time, you know how they used to have houses.
It's kind of like these steps in the old-time house, too.
You got two by sixes there.
That's the old number.
42NC, that's later on, they made a letter.
Right.
See that?
That's the old house, old number yet.
Later on, they made that letter.
Right.
You know, played it.
Uh-huh.
Well, with this house out there, what years were you living out at Global Mine?
Since I was born, I was born in 1900.
We moved out here in 1919.
How many years?
So it's 19 years you lived at the mine site itself.
I said we moved out here in 1919.
I was born out here in 1900, December 21st.
Did your father work in the mine all his life?
No, he didn't.
And then Grandpa, he opened up that lignite mine out there, so Daddy went to work for him.
Grandpa?
Grandpa Vogel, yeah.
Grandpa Vogel.
Yeah, he opened that lignite mine out here with coffee.
clubhouse, I don't know if he went.
He's about two miles from here.
That's the first link that I might fix, they said, you know, on this side of the road, north side of the road.
Right.
Yeah, it's about two miles out here.
Yeah, so daddy went to work for him, you know.
Right.
Went to work for him, him and grandpa's, you know, daughter, yeah, so they got married, you know.
I see.
Yeah, yeah.
So your father married Grandpa Vogel's daughter?
Daughter, yeah.
I see.
Yeah, that's Vogel's grandmother.
My daddy's name is Lawrence, you know.
Right.
Vogel, yeah.
They married, yeah.
Well, what did your dad do at the mine?
Was he a superintendent or a foreman?
Yeah, he was kind of a foreman, yeah.
Did you go to school out at the mines?
School, school.
Yeah, we were taught at which school?
Excuse me, there at the Mines, or did you come in Rockdale?
No, Talbert Ridge School.
That is over here.
I did the country.
About two months you had to work.
What was the name of that school?
Talbert Ridge.
Talbert?
Talbert Ridge.
T-A-L-B-E-R-T?
Yeah, Talbert Ridge.
Talbert Ridge.
Did you go to school three, four months out of the year, or how long did you go to school?
I was a full term.
For the term, let me see, I guess from September, September till, I guess I could have got to school now almost about that long, I believe.
Oh, you did?
Did you like going to school out there?
Yeah.
Did you?
Willie told me yesterday that he played hooky somewhere.
Yeah, he never got there.
He wouldn't go anywhere.
He stayed in the woods, you know.
But you liked to go to school?
Yeah, I went to school.
I went to seventh grade, I think, when I taught out in the country.
Well, they had me play hooky, you know, and Daddy would take the bell out in the morning and finish school with us, you know, and lay it out in the woods till it even didn't come back home, you know.
Well, he said he was sorry now he did that, you know, because he can't do it and write much.
Yeah.
I'm sure he learned a lot out there in the woods.
I don't know, maybe.
Well, did you get along with the Mexican families out there?
Yeah, we done all right.
Well, you lived in a big house then, comparatively speaking, to their houses.
Can you remember how their houses lived?
The other house, they had one room, one kitchen.
One room, one kitchen?
Yeah, just for the, you know, for the...
Grandma owned them houses, you know, and she rented out to the Mexicans, you know.
I see.
Mine belonged to Grandpa.
Grandma and them had them.
I made about 30 houses, I believe.
The Mexicans, they paid rent every two weeks, you know.
They weren't there but two weeks?
They paid rent every two weeks.
I see.
They paid the Mexicans every two weeks.
I see.
Did you go into Rockdale very often or did you stay out of the mine camp most of the time?
I stayed out there most of the time.
So in 1919, what happened?
Did you leave the mines then?
No.
And you came here?
Yes.
And you became a farmer?
Yes, I was a farmer.
Had you saved up some money to buy some land?
No.
Were you a sharecropper, or did you come with your father?
I came with his dad, yeah.
I see.
So he was able to save up some money from working at the mines to buy his own land?
Yeah, he got it all.
We owed some of it.
We got to pay it all, you know.
Can you remember anything about the commissary out there at the mine?
Yeah, kind of something, yeah.
Do you remember what it looked like?
It was just one room building, you know, just one room.
Just made box lumber, you know, just plain building, you know.
What kind of goods were sold at the commissary?
Ah, they sold more just grocery stuff, I believe.
No clothes or anything?
No, I don't blame you.
You were down there only six months, but you must remember some of the hazards of mining.
Were there any dangers down there in the mines?
Not too much.
Down there, you know, some dirt would fall down.
Tunnels, you know, tunnels about that wide, you know.
So down there, some would cave down, you know, and they'd put props under there, you know, to keep from, you know, falling on the workers, yeah.
How was the air down there?
The air?
Was the air bad to breathe, or...?
It was pretty good.
They had a fan, you know, what you call an air shaft, you know, on the other end of the fan, you know.
Put the fresh air in and suck it out, you know.
Sometimes it'd get bad.
Sometimes it would.
Had to, you know, fix it, though, you know.
They make the air shafts or the air go, you know, circulating.
Had a fan run by steam, you know, steam boiler, yeah.
How did the Mexican workers work?
Did they sing while they were working?
Did they work together?
Or did they work by themselves?
Oh, each one worked separately.
See, they got paid by those little cars, you know.
They'd fill, you know, so and so much, you know.
I don't remember how much they got.
About 1,500 pounds in there.
Little cars that run on little wheels, you know.
Yeah.
Little trucks put mules that pull to the shaft, you know.
Right.
They did work by them.
The more they'd fill, you know, the more they'd make, you know.
You see?
And those other ones, they worked by the day.
The other ones?
The other ones, you know.
Not one, but one to hose the coal up and down, you know.
Right.
Dump it out in the railroad car, you know.
I see.
Yeah.
Then they had to have a man down in there, shove them cars on the cage, you know.
So they pull it up and dump it down and let it back down.
And those people, the men who ran the machinery were paid by the day?
They were by the day.
And the Mexicans and the other people who were down in the mines?
Yeah, they worked by the car load, you know.
I see.
The more they fill, the more they make, you know.
Were you a good miner when you were working down here?
Did you mine a lot of coal every day?
I didn't do much.
I done pretty good, I guess, for it.
my age, you know.
I wasn't used to it much.
How come you went down in the mines?
What?
How come you went down in the mines to work?
Because I lived out there.
You couldn't get a job working the machinery?
I don't believe it.
I wasn't old enough.
I wasn't 18.
I wasn't 18 yet.
See, that here former, he wasn't allowed to work nobody unless he was 18 in the mines.
I see.
But that daddy fool, when he had to sign paper in case I got hurt or something, he couldn't complain, you know.
Right.
Well, do you remember Jose Morales?
What?
Do you remember Jose Morales?
I don't believe I remember that Mexican.
Well, he was 15 years old in that big cave-in in 1913.
The what?
The cave-in.
Yeah, cave-in, yeah.
And he was 15 years old.
Yeah.
That was a little young then for Yeah, it was young, but they had to
Oh, they couldn't work unless they was 18, you know.
They had to sign in case they get hurt, you know.
The boys get hurt, they couldn't, you know, pursue them or something, you know, complain, you know.
I see.
They took that chance, yeah.
So Grandpa Vogel would make them sign these release forms.
I see.
Do you remember what the youngest Mexican worker you saw down there was?
Adam B. was in it, and he owned it, that Adam B.
And then Jose was in the Adam B.
How did they use the mules?
Did they take them down in the morning and bring them back?
Yeah, bring them up back in the evening, yeah.
Take them down and bring them back in the evening.
Were they big mules, little mules?
About medium size.
About medium size, okay.
Were they easy animals to work with?
What?
Were they easy animals?
Yeah, they were easy tame mules.
But they had many of them.
They knew what to do, you know, what they had to do.
Would you hitch the mule up to the small coal car?
Yeah, car, and they'd pull it, you know.
To the shaft?
To the shaft, yeah.
On the north side, they didn't have to hitch them in that way, going downhill and cool ones this way and that way, you know.
To the east it goes downhill and south it goes down.
This way goes up, you know.
They had to pull the cars up here with the mules.
It's just ridiculous, you know, coming down the road and down the side pushing.
Was anybody hurt when you were down working in the mine?
No, not that I know of.
Did you pretty much stay to your own house or did you have Mexican friends when you were little?
You know, did you socialize with them?
Yeah, we got along with them, yeah.
We didn't run around with some, you know, but there's some camp there, you know.
How far away was the camp, the Mexican camp, from your house?
Oh, it was close.
It went too far.
Some houses, some houses were, you know, some were close.
What, about 50 yards or something like that?
Yeah.
Did, what kind of entertainment did the Mexicans have?
Do you remember that?
Did they sing or...
If they had weddings, they'd dance, you know.
They'd sing something.
They would play guitar, you know.
Let me ask you this.
What, you know, mining must be really hard work.
What?
Mining must be really hard work.
Yeah, it's hard work, yeah.
So what did you eat, you know, in the morning before you went to the mine, and then at dinner, and then at supper?
What kind of food did you eat?
Ah, we just had like cream of wheat or something like that, you know.
And for breakfast?
Yeah.
And what about for dinner?
Ah, chicken or something else, like that meat, you know.
Would you come up out of the mine to eat, or did you eat your dinner down in the mine?
I came on home, then I went back.
I see.
And then for supper, what did you have?
You wasn't in the mine much.
You was just with Daddy.
I told him I wasn't in that much.
He was too young yet.
I worked in a little while.
I worked in a little while.
They're not allowed to take their children or their sons down there to work unless, you know, they give permission.
They have to be 18.
They have to be 18 before they can work in there, the boys.
Unless their parents want to, you know.
Right.
Because if they might get hurt, they could sue them.
This way they couldn't do that.
By the way, are you Willie's wife?
No, just a sister.
I'm the second oldest.
There's two girls.
I've got a sister who lives uptown.
She's a year older than I am.
We're the two oldest.
Then comes Willie.
Are you Louise?
Uh-huh.
Louise Lawrence?
Do y'all remember Gustav Vogel?
Yes, she's our cousin.
Your cousin.
Gustav Miller.
Why, you know her?
No, I don't.
I just, I heard about her.
I was talking to Miss Beth the other day.
Yes, she's my cousin.
She's Gus Vogel's daughter.
Is she still alive by any chance?
Oh, no, she died 30 years ago or something like that.
No, I may be.
I understand she ran a little school for the Mexican children there.
Yes.
Do you remember anything?
I don't know anything about the school business.
I just know that Billy was out there at the mining camps too, and she'd come out there.
She lived in town.
Right.
And she'd come out there and she'd teach them, but I don't know anything else about it.
I guess they learned their English from Augusta.
Uh-huh.
You lived out at the mines with women.
Do you remember?
The whole family of us lived out there.
My mother and dad and 14 children.
12 children, I think.
There's 14 of us in all of them.
My goodness.
Do you remember any interesting stories, humor stories out there?
You know, growing up or when you were older?
Oh, well, we just played ball a whole lot.
We went crawfishing in the caves, and friends would come out there, and we'd play marbles, and anything a boy would play, we'd play, too.
Were most of your friends... We were mostly boys.
Were most of your friends... We were nine girls, nine girls and three boys in our family.
How did you put up with that, Willie?
Were most of your friends in Rockdale?
Oh, yeah, we know everybody in Rockdale.
Did you have any friends out at the mine?
Well, they wasn't just grown folks.
They had very few children.
Willie Helfer was one of them.
Yeah, I talked to Willie yesterday.
Yeah, he was my oldest sister's age, I believe.
or a year older, and he and Willie chummed a lot.
He'd come to our house, he and his folks.
There wasn't very many white folks living out there, mostly, and Mexicans.
Right.
And we didn't have nothing to do with it.
Oh, you didn't?
Chum rockin' things out of maybe.
Willie was telling me he learned Mexican, you know, the Spanish language really.
Yeah.
Daddy did too, and mother, and I can speak pretty good.
I can tell you the name of any kind of vegetable.
We sold them vegetables.
We had a little express wagon, you know.
Did you have a garden out by your house there?
Yeah, we had a big garden and lots of pretty flowers.
Daddy was a flower lover.
He had lots of pretty flowers.
We kids had to do the watering, you know.
Well, did the Mexicans have their own gardens, too?
Some, but they grown mostly...
Hot peppers.
Hot peppers and...
Squash.
Squash, something like that.
Squash and what do you call them, cassaws?
That's what they grown mostly.
But you didn't have very much contact with the Mexicans?
No, no.
As far as speaking with them, you know, like you and I together, we couldn't do that.
Oh, really?
But we learned, you know, like good morning, good evening, and any kind of vegetable.
Any kind of vegetable.
Did many of them learn?
We had cattle.
We had cows, and we sold them milk and butter.
And they paid you cash for it?
Uh-huh.
Did you trade at the commissary store?
Yeah, there was a little one right in our house, our grandmother's house.
And we did trading there.
And they also had, in those days,
The meat market in town here, he had a wagon team, and he'd come out there selling meat, go around the camp, sell meat.
The ice man would come out and sell ice.
The silver water man would come out there and sell soda water.
The ice cream man would come out there.
The lady sold bonnets and clothing.
She'd come out there, take orders.
You know, anybody that had something to sell had to come out there.
Even the man at Christmas time would come with a whole load of Christmas trees.
Oh, wow.
And the Mexicans would buy Christmas trees?
Yeah, yeah.
Some of them had horses and buggies of their own, and some didn't.
We all walked the town a lot, you know.
I said it was three miles.
I don't know how far it was.
It really was.
I'd say it was three miles.
And we'd walk along the railroad or along the dirt road.
It wasn't but a dirt road.
It wasn't down then.
But after 1919, y'all didn't do any more mining?
No, we moved out here then, 1919.
Do you prefer farming to mining?
Yes.
Why is that?
Well, the doctor told Daddy he had to get out of that hole.
He wouldn't live there long.
Why was that?
Did he pick up a disease or something?
No, you know, but...
He'd always get headaches, so I guess that A in there.
The gas, you know, mines have gas in them.
Yeah, the headache, you know.
So your Daddy went down in the mine?
Uh-huh.
He was a...
kind of boss of the Mexicans.
Grandfather made him boss.
Did he have any trouble with Mexicans?
No.
That's where he learned to speak Spanish, you know.
I see.
We're German.
Right.
And we could speak, us older kids all learned how to speak German.
And then we learned how to speak some Spanish and English.
We could speak three languages.
Grandmother used to, in the First World War I was on,
She took German newspapers.
And her children all got married and left home and left her there by herself.
So mother said, from now on, you and Martha are going to have to go one night you go, stay with them, and the other night Louise go and stay with them.
So we did that.
Every night she'd read the news to us in German, you know, tell us what it's about.
About the war.
And I got so I really could live, too.
The newspaper writing, you know, print is more like in German.
But letter writing has got too many hooks and crooks I see.
I never did learn how to write it or read it either.
Only thing I can read is Dear Friend, Dear Friend, Leave a Friend.
That's all I can read.
Well, when you left the mines, did you pretty much forget about the mines?
Or did you keep in contact?
Yeah, we kind of forgot after a while.
Well, mostly all the mines closed up then, didn't they?
Yeah.
Yeah, they closed up in the Depression, pretty much.
They closed up during the 1930s.
They got oil afterwards and they couldn't sell any more coal, you know.
They got oil cheaper, you know, cleaner.
Couldn't sell any more coal.
Couldn't make no money.
What do you think about shale oil coming in now and running again?
You know, shale oil coming in again.
Yeah, I guess all right now.
coal would be worse, you know, and the oil is so high now.
Them, they could get oil cheap, you know.
Get oil cheaper.
Did you use coal in your stove in your house?
We used it in the heater.
We used lignite coal in the heater.
But you didn't use it to cook with?
No, not the cook stove.
Had lots of timber there.
They made their own ties, what you call it, little ties to put the railroad on.
And they made their own.
They had a little saw mill, too, there, right at the boiler house.
And they used steam out of the boiler, you know.
Right, right.
And made their own ties.
And then what they cut off, you know, they'd cut into blocks for us for stove wood, for grandmother and us.
And they'd haul it up to the house.
And we kids would chop it in sizes for the stove.
That sounds good.
Do you remember anything about, I know you worked at the Vogel Mines, you know, for the first 19 years, or you lived there.
Do you remember anything about the Texas Coal Company?
Texas Coal Company, where was that at?
Down here, just south of 79, it's about a mile down.
Yeah, I know.
They were all around there.
Yeah, down in that bay.
But which one was the Texas Coal Company?
But I don't remember.
It was...
where the Rogel mine was up on the hill, the Stribble mine.
The Texas might have been on the other side, further down, you know, further east.
Seemed like it was.
Further east, yeah, down in there.
There's the Rogel, Texas mine.
In the north of the coal mine, it is up this way, across the railroad.
The Whirly mine, the Big Lump mine.
Big Lump was down at what side of the creek, which was the land, you know, on the north side of the railroad.
Close to the
That's close to where Texas Coal is south of Sandy Creek.
Yeah, what is?
The Texas Coal Company was south of Sandy Creek.
Yeah, that might have been, yeah, that might have been in Texas down in there.
The one of mine, Dr. Dunkey had a mine.
There was some more of mine, but I don't remember there.
I was too young, you know, for the early, maybe, I don't know.
I did remember all the names, but I can't think of them all right now.
I'm getting old too.
I'm forgetting.
Well, that's what we're trying to do here is get all that information down.
I said whenever we all be gone, the younger folks won't know a thing about it.
When you tell them now about it, they look at you like you're telling them a fib or something.
I don't know.
They're too much in a hurry nowadays, I guess.
Too much in a hurry.
So you don't miss the coal mining.
You'd much rather be a farmer.
Well, we couldn't get in that age.
We ain't going to be much of anything, I presume.
Y'all look pretty spry to me.
What happened to your old house there at the Vogel Mine?
After a while, they tore it down.
When grandmother died,
They tore it down and built another room onto her house.
That's Grandmother Vogel.
Uh-huh.
And we moved in there.
We lived in there until we moved over here.
Then Gus Vogel moved out there.
Uncle Gus, he moved in that house after he died afterwards.
He moved out here, Henry Brown, you know.
His daughter married Henry Brown, B-R-A-H-M, Brown.
Right.
He lives west of town, right?
No, right here.
Right out here.
Right over there, Underpass.
Underpass, you know.
Across the railroad.
But he passed away last year.
If you go to that one boy, he could take you out there.
He owned all that old land, most of it.
He could take you down to the mines, show you some of them.
But Underpass here.
Right.
It's right on the right, on the south side of the Raywood.
You can see the house.
It's a trailer house sitting there.
It is close to the Raywood, Ron Henry Brown.
He's not there all the way.
He works on the Raywood most of the time.
John Henry.
John Henry.
He's the only one left of that family in.
John Henry?
Yeah.
You say he might be there today?
He had bad luck last year.
Henry Bromiself died, his son died, and then his wife ran into a bus here, and she got killed.
And all that's left is John Henry?
John Henry and her, his brother's wife's children.
I believe there's two of them, two boys.
So Robert doesn't live there anymore?
Robert and I.
Okay.
Yeah, well, that one boy used to go out to sea.
I don't know.
He's not there always.
He works on the railroad, you know, at Taylor.
Then he comes in.
Sometimes he has to stay at night, you know.
See, John Henry's mother was our cousin, too.
That was Augusta Vogel's sister.
I see.
John Henry, that was Augusta Vogel.
That was her mama.
That was his mama.
Minner, Minner, yeah, not Gustav Minner.
Minner Roper, that was, Minner and Gustav were sisters, you know.
That's M-I-N-A.
Uh-huh.
Yeah, Minner, yeah, that was, Minner, that was his mom, Minner Roper.
He seemed like, he was a real pet.
Yeah, Henry Brown, he owned most of that land out there, and he might take you on to the old,
Richard's mine, that's just right from his house, that direction, you know, not too far.
One thing I want to ask, how did y'all get medical service out there tonight?
Oh, they had a company doctor, you know, in Rockdale.
A company doctor, he'd come out there every two weeks, each Mexican, he had a family, he had to pay 50 cents every payday, you know.
And
Daddy didn't pay too, you know, every two weeks paid that doctor 50 cents.
And if somebody gets sick and he had to come on out, it would cost him any more, you know.
It wouldn't cost him?
No, any more, no.
Anyway, where's the medicine?
At the drugstore.
It was made out there.
They paid so much a month, and they got the medicine for so much.
Where did they get their medicine?
At the commissary?
No, at Tom's.
At the drugstore.
